<author><name><![CDATA[Memblers]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-11-19T01:02:03-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-11-19T01:02:03-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8318&amp;p=86516#p86516</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8318&amp;p=86516#p86516"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Big nose caveman with Nes PowerPak]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8318&amp;p=86516#p86516"><![CDATA[
To hack a palette, you need to find where it is stored in the ROM.  The easiest way is to use an emulator that lets you view the palette while the game is running (not only the colors, but the actual byte values).<br /><br />So if the first 4 bytes of the palette are $0D,$10,$15,$2B (just random numbers for example), use the hex editor to search for that pattern in the ROM.  Various games could be different, but <em>normally</em> you would expect to find a bunch of sets of 4 colors, in a format like: background color, byte 1, byte 2, byte 3.  Find that pattern, and hex edit it.  But the different palette sets could be scattered throughout the ROM also, or may be stored in reverse order, it just depends on the program.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Sat Nov 19, 2011 1:02 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
